Excellent! I quadrupled the recipe for tomorrow night's New Year's Eve party. I wasn't able to get lamb shoulder so I cubed two large Costco legs of lamb. I followed the ingredients exactly. Since I made so much I needed to use two Le Creuset pots. As for the last step - reducing the broth: After the initial 1 hour of cooking, I scooped out the broth and reduced it in a separate pan and then put the reduced, thickened broth back in the stew. This was to prevent the chickpeas from getting mushy. Not sure it was worth the trouble but my two huge pots of stew are FABULOUS! Several of my 21 guests are bringing complimentary dishes including a pearl couscous dish and steamed green beans.

Rating: 4
This was one of the best recipes that I've made in a long while. It was even better than I thought it would be, given the rave reviews. I did make a couple of changes - not big - because I didn't want the dish to be too sweet and I wanted additional veggies. So, I reduced the apricots to about 1/3 cup, chopped them coarsely; added a few chopped, pitted prunes; and, added about 3 big carrots cut into chunks. I found that I didn't need to simmer the dish to reduce the sauce - it was already fairly thick. I used chopped parsley instead of cilantro. Served with roasted cauliflower and whole wheat couscous. Really, really delicious. My 14 year old daughter loved it as did our 90 year old guest! A big time keeper.

